title: Tesla shifts to online sales, lowers price of Model 3
text: CNBC's Phil LeBeau reports on the latest from Tesla. Among the headlines, Tesla is phasing out its physical dealerships across the country and trying to shift sales to online. The company also announced that they will sell the Model 3 at $35,000. Musk says he expects to sell half a million Model 3 cars worldwide.

title: Here’s everything that just happened at Tesla
text: Elon Musk has fulfilled a decade-long goal with the $35,000 Model 3. Dozens of changes to Tesla came along with it.

title: Tesla's new online-only model faces challenges
text: David Whiston, a Morningstar analyst, reacts to Tesla Inc.'s plan to shut many of its stores to help deliver a new Model 3 for $35,000. He speaks with Bloomberg's Emily Chang and Shery Ahn on "Bloomberg Technology."

title: Elon Musk changes his name to Elon Tusk
text: Tesla CEO Elon Musk has changed his Twitter handle to Elon Tusk.

title: Elon Musk launches $35,000 Tesla Model 3
text: Tesla Inc. is finally putting a $35,000 version of the Model 3 sedan on the market, almost three years after Chief Executive Officer Elon Musk started taking orders for the sedan. Loup Ventures co-founder Gene Munster and Bloomberg's Keith Naughton discuss on "Bloomberg Technology."

title: Tesla launches $35K Model 3 with shorter range, new interior
text: CNBC's Phil LeBeau reports on the news from Tesla. With CNBC's Melissa Lee and the Fast Money traders, Tim Seymour, Steve Grasso, Dan Nathan and Guy Adami.

title: Elon Musk takes to twitter to tease Tesla news
text: Zach Guzman and Kristin Myers of Yahoo Finance and Michael Block of Third Seven Advisors discuss what the latest news might be from Tesla.

title: What's important for investors as Tesla controversy continues with SEC
text: Bernstein's Toni Sacconaghi discusses Tesla's stock performance after controversies from Musk's tweets and questions as to whether the company can be profitable long term.

title: Tesla faces some money woes with a nearly $1 billion debt payment due Friday
text: Tesla's debt deadline hits this week. With CNBC's Phil LeBeau and Melissa Lee, and the Fast Money traders, Pete Najarian, Tim Seymour, Steve Grasso and Guy Adami.

title: CNBC Tech Check Morning Edition
text: CNBC's Tech Check brings you the latest in tech news from CNBC's 1 Market in the heart of San Francisco.

title: Elon Musk SEC drama is a 'sideshow for the fundamental investor', says Bernstein's Sacconaghi
text: Toni Sacconaghi, Bernstein senior analyst, joins 'Fastautos Money Halftime Report' to discuss the SEC holding Tesla CEO Elon Musk in contempt after it found he violated their deal.

title: Jim Cramer's thoughts on Home Depot, Macy's, Tesla, Indra Nooyi and Nikki Haley
text: Jim Cramer's tackling the top headlines from Tuesday morning.

title: SEC wants judge to hold Elon Musk in contempt over tweets
text: Former prosecutor David Bruno on the SEC asking a federal judge to hold Tesla CEO Elon Musk in contempt over his recent tweets.

title: Elon Musk is in hot water with the SEC again over tweets
text: Andy Serwer of Yahoo Finance breaks down why Elon Musk's tweets are an issue with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission. The SEC is questioning recent tweets which state that Tesla would produce 500,000 cars this year.

title: Former SEC commissioner weighs in on the SEC allegations against Elon Musk
text: The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission is asking the court to hold Tesla CEO Elon Musk in contempt. The S.E.C. says that Musk violated their December agreement by tweeting about Tesla without approval.

title: Musk faces U.S. SEC contempt claim over two tweets
text: Elon Musk faces a fresh round of regulatory trouble with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission for tweets about Tesla Inc. Bloomberg Intelligence's Matthew Bloxham reports on "Bloomberg Surveillance."

title: SEC wants Elon Musk to be held in contempt of court for allegedly violating December agreement
text: The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission is asking the court to hold Tesla CEO Elon Musk in contempt. The S.E.C. says that Musk violated their December agreement by tweeting about Tesla without approval. Musk is firing back, tweeting multiple times about the allegations. CNBC's Phil LeBeau reports.

title: Apple Co-Founder Wozniak on Zuckerberg, AI, Crypto
text: Apple Inc. Co-Founder Steve Wozniak discusses how he lost respect for Facebook Inc. Chief Executive Officer Mark Zuckerberg after his congressional testimony. He also comments on the future of AI, tech startups, cryptocurrencies, and Apple's next innovation.

title: Musk will not be forced to leave Tesla over tweets, CFRA Analyst Says
text: The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission on Monday asked a judge to hold Musk in contempt for violating a settlement that required him to get Tesla Inc.’s approval before communicating material information to investors.

title: Elon Musk a message case for the SEC, says former SEC deputy chief of staff
text: Michael Liftik, Quinn Emanuel Trial Lawyers, and Russell Duncan, Shulman Rogers, discuss what the likely SEC response will be following Tesla CEO Elon Musk's latest comments on Twitter.

title: Tesla facing more trauma after Elon Musk's latest Twitter rant
text: Elon Musk's tweet puts Twitter in danger. Is his job as CEO at risk? With CNBC's Phil LeBeau and Melissa Lee, and the Fast Money traders, Tim Seymour, Brian Kelly, Karen Finerman and Guy Adami.

title: "Shut up Elon!" Tesla investor pleads on Elon Musk tweeting
text: Ross Gerber of Gerber Kawasaki Wealth Management discusses the frustration over Elon Musk's tweeting and the SEC asking a judge to hold Musk in contempt of court over his latest tweet.

title: Musk problem bigger than market realizes, says expert
text: CNBC's "Power Lunch" team discusses how much trouble Tesla CEO Elon Musk is in and what this may mean for investors, with Jeff Sonnenfeld, senior associate dean of Yale School of Management, and Matt DeLorenzo, managing editor of Kelley Blue Book.

title: Full interview with Lee Cooperman on Elon Musk (Tesla) & Amazon.
text: Lee Cooperman, Omega Advisors founder, chairman and CEO, sits down with CNBC's Leslie Picker to discuss his long-term economic concerns, shares his thoughts on socialism and on market conditions.

title: Elon Musk has been pushing the SEC deal for the last few months, says WSJ's Higgins
text: The Wall Street Journal's Tim Higgins and CNBC's Phil LeBeau join Kelly Evans on 'The Exchange' to discuss the situation between the SEC and Tesla CEO Elon Musk after the SEC says Elon Musk violated their deal.

title: Cramer: Elon Musk should be removed from Tesla as CEO for attacking the SEC
text: The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission is asking the court to hold Tesla CEO Elon Musk in contempt. The S.E.C. says that Musk violated their December agreement by tweeting about Tesla without approval. Musk is firing back, tweeting multiple times about the allegations. CNBC's Jim Cramer weighs in on the situation.

title: Lee Cooperman: Elon Musk has to behave like an adult
text: Lee Cooperman, Omega Advisors founder, chairman and CEO, sits down with CNBC's Leslie Picker to discuss the situation between Tesla CEO Elon Musk and the SEC.

title: Warren Buffett: Electric cars are in America's future
text: In an interview with CNBC's Becky Quick and Joe Kernan, Berkshire Hathaway's Chairman and CEO Warren Buffett addresses why he has invested in autos and electric cars in China more than in the United States. Buffett addresses the future of electric cars in America and how the operation to create more solar powered cars differs in America than in China.

title: Musk's SpaceX launches second Falcon 9 rocket this year
text: Tesla's Model 3 has dragged the company's stock lower. Luckily, Musk can look to SpaceX's successful launch of its second Falcon 9 rocket of this year. Yahoo Finance's Dan Roberts, Kristin Myers, and Heidi Chung break down the details.

title: Model 3 loses Consumer Reports recommendation
text: Heidi Chung, Kristin Myers and Dan Roberts of Yahoo Finance discuss Consumer Reports not recommending Tesla's Model 3 and some of the challenges facing the company.

title: Musk is over-promising on autonomous vehicles, says AutoNation CEO Mike Jackson
text: AutoNation CEO Mike Jackson criticized Tesla CEO Elon Musk's marketing of his autonomous vehicles as well as his practice of taking orders on the Model 3.

title: Elon Musk gives timeline for fully autonomous cars
text: Tasha Keeney Ark investment analyst discusses her interview with Elon Musk and the Tesla timeline for full autonomous vehicles, regulation and Tesla production.

title: Tesla shares tumble after Consumer Reports rips Model 3
text: The Car Coach Lauren Fix on how Tesla shares fell, after Consumer Reports says it will no longer recommend the Model 3 due to reliability issues.

title: Tesla's Model 3 loses consumer reports recommendation
text: Tesla Inc.’s Model 3 lost a coveted recommendation from Consumer Reports, dropping its brand from the top 10 of the magazine’s annual ranking. Bloomberg's Chester Dawson reports on "Bloomberg Technology."

title: Consumer Reports no longer recommends the Tesla Model 3
text: Shares of Tesla fell as as Consumer Reports said it could no longer recommend the auto manufacturer's Model 3 electric car. The report compiled thousands of owner reviews and found that build quality was the biggest reason to take away the recommendation.

title: Tesla no longer recommended by Consumer Reports partly due to liability issue
text: Consumer Reports pulls its recommendation for Tesla's Model 3 vehicle due to a number of issues. CNBC's Phil LeBeau reports.

title: Wall Street is focusing too much on Tesla's production
text: Tasha Keeney, Ark Invest analyst, and Bloomberg's Craig Trudell discuss the road ahead for Tesla Inc. with Bloomberg's Emily Chang on "Bloomberg Technology."

title: Elon Musk revises Tesla's production forecast that was tweeted incorrectly
text: Jen Rogers, Myles Udland and Andy Serwer discuss the challenges facing Tesla.

title: Tesla general counsel's departure adds to list of executive exits under Musk
text: Phil Lebeau reports on the departure of Tesla's general counsel, an addition to a growing list of executives to depart the automaker under the leadership of CEO Elon Musk. Joseph Osha of JMP Securities and Craig Irwin of Roth Capital debate whether Tesla's business will continue to be successful.

title: Tesla bear Gordon Johnson sees shares falling to $72
text: Gordon Johnson, Vertical Group analyst, explains why he is shorting Tesla Inc. shares. He speaks with Bloomberg's Caroline Hyde and Lisa Abramowicz on "Bloomberg Markets: The Close."

title: Elon Musk tends to be more accurate
text: Karl Brauer of Kelley Blue Book, and CNBC's Phil LeBeau join 'The Exchange' to discuss their expectations for Tesla after Tesla CEO Elon Musk tweeted his plans for the company.

title: Musk tweets about production then scales back forecast
text: Melody Hahn, Myles Udland and Dan Roberts of Yahoo Finance discusses Elon Musk's tweet about production and the culture of Tesla.

title: Tesla executive turnover continues under Musk
text: CNBC's Phil LeBeau reports on turnover in Tesla as General Counsel Dane Butswinkas resigns after just two months on the job.

title: Why investors shouldn't worry about Elon Musk
text: Cathie Wood of Ark Invest sits down with "Squawk Box" to discuss her recent interview with Elon Musk and what she thinks about the trajectory of Tesla.

title: Tesla general counsel departure shows company struggles to retain top talent, Gene Munster says
text: In a continuation of Tesla's trend of leadership turnover, General Counsel Dane Butswinkas is leaving the company. Gene Munster of Loup Ventures joins "Squawk Box" with his analysis on the news.

title: Tesla will likely get bought by a tech company, analyst says | Squawk Box Europe
text: Freddie Lait, chief investment officer at Latitude Investment Management, said it was "possible" Apple or another tech company could buy Tesla.

title: Tesla general counsel leaves after 2 months on the job
text: In a continuation of Tesla's trend of leadership turnover, General Counsel Dane Butswinkas is leaving the company. CNBC's Phil LeBeau reports.

title: Tesla reportedly plans to offer Model 3 leasing
text: In an email to employees, Tesla announced that employees will be able to lease Model 3 within the next two weeks. The company said that the leasing program may be available to the public as soon as this year.

title: Musk hits send too soon on Tesla production forecast
text: Elon Musk needed to correct a prediction for the amount of cars Tesla Inc. would produce in 2019 just hours after tweeting that production would reach about 500,000 vehicles this year. Bloomberg Opinion columnist Alex Webb reports on "Bloomberg Surveillance." His opinions are his own.

title: The secret to why a Tesla costs so much (Hint: Batteries)
text: One of the biggest things preventing Elon Musk from releasing a mass market electric vehicle comes down to the vehicle's blessing and curse: its lithium-ion battery. We break down the science and the cost.
